          "body": "The chapter's central drama is the movement of the *kavod* — the divine glory. It does not vanish; it moves in stages, and each stage is narrated with spatial precision. From 'above the cherub' (the Holy of Holies position) the glory rises to the threshold (v.4). After the chariot-throne description, it moves from the threshold back over the cherubim (v.18) and then to the east gate (v.19). The departure will not be complete until 11:23, when the glory stands on the mountain east of the city. This staged withdrawal is theologically deliberate. God does not abandon His people in an instant. The Deuteronomic covenant had warned that disobedience would result in the withdrawal of the LORD's presence and blessing (Deuteronomy 28:15-68; cf. 31:17 — 'I will hide my face from them'). What Ezekiel sees is that warning being fulfilled with agonizing deliberateness. Spurgeon observed that when God departs from a church, the departure is often gradual — the candle grows dim before it goes out. The east gate position of verse 19 is the penultimate pause: the glory is still visible, still accessible in principle, but has left the innermost sanctuary. The question that pause poses to every reader is: *At what stage in this movement are we?*"
