          "body": "Ezekiel 10 stands at the canonical intersection of three great theological narratives. Behind it stands the Sinai tradition: the same glory-cloud that filled the tabernacle (Exodus 40:34-35) and the temple (1 Kings 8:11) is now the same cloud departing. The departure signals what Moses himself had warned (Leviticus 26:11-12 reversed): 'I will set My dwelling among you' has given way to 'I will abandon my dwelling among you.' Alongside it stands the parallel of 1 Samuel 4:21-22 — the *Ichabod* moment when the ark was captured and Phinehas's wife named her son 'the glory has departed.' Ezekiel 10 is *Ichabod* on an eschatological scale. But ahead of it stands the great reversal: Ezekiel 43:1-5, when the glory returns by the same east gate; and ultimately, John 1:14 — *the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us, and we beheld His glory*. The Incarnation is the definitive return of the kavod. What departed from the temple in Ezekiel 10 returned in the person of Jesus of Nazareth, who cleansed the same temple courts (John 2:13-17) and whose own body became the new temple (John 2:21). The departure of Ezekiel 10 is not the last word — it is the penultimate word. The last word is the glory returning in flesh."
